You picked up a pencil once in third grade, drew a lopsided house, and thought, "Yeah, I'm an artist." Cute story, bro. But you're not in art class anymore. You're stepping into the algorithmic trenches, where the canvas isn't paper—it's a coordinate grid that will skull-drag you if you don't learn its rules. You want to make generative art that makes jaws drop? You gotta survive bootcamp first.

Still with me, or you zoning out already? Good. Let's strip this down to the brass tacks.

## Core Carnage (Rip Apart the Essentials)

You think you can just open a text editor and start splashing pixels around? Oh, sure, skip the basics—because mediocrity's a great look on you. You need to know the battlefield before you pull the trigger. p5.js is your weapon. It’s a JavaScript library built to make coding visual for artists and designers, but don't let the friendly intro fool you. Under the hood, it’s a ruthless rendering engine. If you feed it garbage logic, it will spit out a blank screen and laugh at you.

### The Two Modes: Global vs. Instance

Listen up, chief. p5.js gives you two ways to enter the ring. 

**Global Mode** is the default. It’s the bare-knuckle street fight. You just drop your functions right into the global scope.

```javascript
function setup() {
  createCanvas(800, 600);
}

function draw() {
  background(0);
  circle(mouseX, mouseY, 50);
}
```

Simple, right? Maybe too simple. Global mode pollutes the namespace. Every variable you declare globally is a loaded gun pointed at your own foot. You write `var speed` up top, and boom—some other library or script just hijacked it. 

Enter **Instance Mode**. This is the tactical, silenced-assassin approach. You wrap your entire sketch in a function, locking your variables in a tight little cage where nobody else can touch them. 

```javascript
const sketch = (p) => {
  let speed = 2;

  p.setup = () => {
    p.createCanvas(800, 600);
  };

  p.draw = () => {
    p.background(0);
    p.circle(p.mouseX, p.mouseY, 50);
  };
};

new p5(sketch);
```

> ⚠️ **Common Mistake:** Copy-pasting Global Mode sketches into a modern React or Vue app and watching the whole DOM burn to the ground. If you're embedding p5.js anywhere near other code, Instance Mode isn't an option. It's a survival requirement.

You see the difference? Instance mode makes you prefix everything with `p.`. It looks tedious, but it’s your armor. If you’re just prototyping in the p5 Web Editor, go global. But the second you ship this to a real webpage, suit up with Instance Mode.

### The Grid: Owning the Coordinate Origin

Let me guess—you think (0,0) is the center of the screen? Highkey delusional. This isn't high school geometry. In p5.js, (0,0) is the top-left corner. Always has been. Always will be.

X moves right. Y moves down. Wrap your head around that right now, because the moment you try to plot a shape and it flies off the screen, it's because you assumed Y goes up. It doesn't. Y goes down like your motivation on a Monday morning.

You want to move the origin? You want (0,0) in the center where it belongs? You manipulate the canvas. 

```javascript
function setup() {
  createCanvas(800, 600);
  // Move the origin to the center of the canvas
  translate(width / 2, height / 2);
}
```

Wait, no! Stop! If you put `translate()` in `setup()`, it only happens once. The canvas resets its matrix every time `draw()` runs. We'll get to that in a second, but understand this: `width` and `height` are built-in variables. They tell you the size of your war zone. Use them. Never hardcode `400` when you mean `width / 2`. You change the canvas size later, and your whole sketch breaks. Be smarter than the code.

### Canvas Size and Pixel Density

You think an 800x600 canvas is just 800 by 600 pixels? Oh, you sweet summer child. Welcome to the era of high-DPI displays. Your fancy MacBook Retina screen doesn't render one pixel per pixel—it renders two. Or three! If you don't control your pixel density, your crisp generative lines will look like blurry garbage.

By default, p5.js calls `pixelDensity(displayDensity())`. It tries to match your monitor. Sometimes that’s fine. But when you start doing heavy pixel manipulation later in this journey, that 2x density will melt your frame rate into slag.

> 💡 **Pro Tip:** Force `pixelDensity(1)` in your `setup()` if you care about raw performance over hyper-crisp edges. It halves the pixel workload. Your GPU will thank you.

### The Lifecycle: setup() vs draw()

This is the heart of the beast. The engine. The lifecycle. If you don't get this, you're just a tourist taking screenshots.

`setup()` runs exactly once. One time. One trigger pull. You set up your environment here. Canvas size, frame rate, loading fonts, initializing arrays. You do NOT draw shapes in `setup()`. You don't animate in `setup()`. It’s the prep work before the brawl.

`draw()` runs on a loop. Over. And over. And over. By default, it tries to run 60 times a second. 60 frames per second. Every time `draw()` fires, it draws a new frame. If you don't clear the screen, it just draws over the last frame. 

```javascript
function setup() {
  createCanvas(800, 600);
  background(25); // Dark grey background, runs ONCE
}

function draw() {
  // No background() here!
  circle(mouseX, mouseY, 20);
}
```

What happens here? You get a trailing trail of circles following your mouse. Why? Because the canvas isn't being wiped. The previous frame bleeds into the next one. It's a slick trick for motion blur, but if you actually want a static shape moving across a clean background, you better put `background()` inside `draw()`.

> 🎯 **Key Insight:** The `draw()` loop is an illusion. It's not a continuous flow of ink. It's a flipbook. Every frame, p5.js renders the entire state of your canvas. If your code is slow, the flipbook stutters. That stutter is called "dropping frames."

### Frame Rate: Your Leash

You think you're the boss of the canvas? You're not. The frame rate is your leash. `frameRate(60)` sets the target. But if your `draw()` function has to calculate 10,000 particle collisions, it’s going to take longer than 16.67 milliseconds. And when it takes longer, the frame rate drops. 

You can check your real-time FPS with `frameRate()`. Print it to the console. Watch it. If it dips below 60, your code is bloated. You're asking the browser to do too much heavy lifting. 

Excuses? Cute. But winners bleed sweat, not stories. If your sketch lags, you optimize. You don't blame the browser. 

### Input: Proving It Ain't a Static Screenshot

A painting is dead. A generative sketch breathes. It reacts. It bites back. If your art doesn't respond to the user, it’s just a screenshot with extra steps.

p5.js hands you `mouseX` and `mouseY` on a silver platter. Two built-in variables that constantly update with the cursor's position. Use them. 

But what about clicks? What about the keyboard?

```javascript
function mousePressed() {
  // This fires ONCE per click. Not every frame.
  console.log("BANG!");
}

function keyPressed() {
  // Fires once when a key goes down.
  if (key === ' ') {
    console.log("Spacebar hit.");
  }
}
```

> ⚠️ **Common Mistake:** Putting input logic directly inside `draw()` without state tracking. If you check `if (mouseIsPressed)` inside `draw()`, it will fire 60 times a second while the button is held down. If you want a single action per click, use the `mousePressed()` event function. Period.

You want to map the spacebar to reset the canvas? Put it in `keyPressed()`. You want a particle to spawn continuously while the mouse is down? Use `mouseIsPressed` inside `draw()`. Know the difference. Own the input.

## Street Smarts (How to Wield This in the Wild)

Alright, dreamer. You got the theory. You know the lifecycle. You know the grid. Now let's get our hands dirty. I'm not letting you copy-paste a tutorial. We're going to build a reactive, frame-rate-aware sketch from scratch, and I'm going to explain every single scalpel cut.

### The Scenario: The Pulse Bomb

We’re going to build a pulse bomb. A circle that sits in the dead center of the canvas, pulsing based on a sine wave. When you click the mouse, it explodes outward, resetting the pulse. When you hit 'R', the background flips. And we’re going to do it in Instance Mode, because we aren't amateurs.

**Step 1: The Setup and the Armor**

Open a blank file. We define the sketch closure.

```javascript
const pulseBomb = (p) => {
  let pulseRadius = 50;
  let bgColor = 10;

  p.setup = () => {
    p.createCanvas(p.windowWidth, p.windowHeight);
    p.frameRate(60);
    p.noStroke();
  };
```

Look at that. `p.windowWidth` and `p.windowHeight`. We aren't hardcoding 800x600. We're taking up the whole damn browser window. We set the frame rate to 60 to establish the leash. `p.noStroke()` because outlines are for coloring books, and we want clean, filled shapes.

**Step 2: The Draw Loop and the Math**

Now we need the pulse. How do you make a circle breathe? You use `p.sin()`. Sine waves oscillate between -1 and 1. We map that to a radius.

```javascript
  p.draw = () => {
    p.background(bgColor);

    // Move origin to center
    p.translate(p.width / 2, p.height / 2);

    // Calculate the pulse
    // p.frameCount is a built-in variable that counts frames.
    let pulse = p.sin(p.frameCount * 0.05) * 50;
    let currentRadius = pulseRadius + pulse;

    p.fill(255, 0, 0); // Red like blood
    p.circle(0, 0, currentRadius * 2); // circle takes diameter, not radius!
  };
```

Did you catch that? `p.circle()` takes the diameter, not the radius. How many rookies have screwed that up? Millions. You multiply by 2, or you look like a fool with a tiny dot on the screen.

Also, notice `p.background(bgColor)` is inside `draw()`. This wipes the slate clean every single frame. Without it, the red circle would smear across the screen as it pulses. We want a clean pulse, so we wipe it.

**Step 3: The Interaction**

A pulsing circle is nice. But it's still just a screensaver. Let's make it violent. When the user clicks, we want the radius to spike.

```javascript
  p.mousePressed = () => {
    // Only trigger if the click is inside the canvas
    if (p.mouseX > 0 && p.mouseX < p.width && p.mouseY > 0 && p.mouseY < p.height) {
      pulseRadius = 150; // Spike the radius
    }
  };
```

Wait, if we just set `pulseRadius = 150`, it will stay at 150 forever. The pulse will just be bigger. We need it to decay back to normal. We add a decay mechanic inside `draw()`.

Update the `draw()` loop:

```javascript
  p.draw = () => {
    p.background(bgColor);
    p.translate(p.width / 2, p.height / 2);

    let pulse = p.sin(p.frameCount * 0.05) * 50;
    let currentRadius = pulseRadius + pulse;

    p.fill(255, 0, 0);
    p.circle(0, 0, currentRadius * 2);

    // Decay the radius back to 50
    if (pulseRadius > 50) {
      pulseRadius -= 2; // Shrink by 2 pixels every frame
    }
  };
```

Now we're talking. You click, the circle balloons to 150, and then it shrinks by 2 pixels every frame until it settles back at 50. It's alive. It reacts.

**Step 4: The Keyboard Flank**

Let's wire up the 'R' key to reset the background. 

```javascript
  p.keyPressed = () => {
    if (p.key === 'r' || p.key === 'R') {
      bgColor = p.random(0, 50); // Random dark background
    }
  };
```

> ☕ **Real Talk:** Notice I didn't just say `if (key == 'r')`. Users hit Caps Lock. Users hold Shift. You check for both, or your app feels broken. Details matter, chief. The streets are unforgiving.

**Step 5: The Window Resize Trap**

You think you're done? You refresh the page, it looks beautiful. Then you resize your browser window. What happens? The canvas stays the same size, or it distorts. You forgot the resize handler.

```javascript
  p.windowResized = () => {
    p.resizeCanvas(p.windowWidth, p.windowHeight);
  };
```

Boom. Now when the user stretches the browser, the canvas stretches with it. The origin recalculates to the new center every frame because we used `p.width / 2` in `draw()`. Flexible. Lethal. Unbreakable.

### The Full Arsenal

Here is the complete, unadulterated code. Read it. Understand it. Do not copy it without tracing every single line with your own eyes.

```javascript
const pulseBomb = (p) => {
  let pulseRadius = 50;
  let bgColor = 10;

  p.setup = () => {
    p.createCanvas(p.windowWidth, p.windowHeight);
    p.frameRate(60);
    p.noStroke();
  };

  p.draw = () => {
    p.background(bgColor);
    p.translate(p.width / 2, p.height / 2);

    let pulse = p.sin(p.frameCount * 0.05) * 50;
    let currentRadius = pulseRadius + pulse;

    // Color shifts from red to white as it expands
    let colorShift = p.map(currentRadius, 50, 200, 0, 255);
    p.fill(255, colorShift, colorShift);

    p.circle(0, 0, currentRadius * 2);

    if (pulseRadius > 50) {
      pulseRadius -= 2;
    }
  };

  p.mousePressed = () => {
    if (p.mouseX > 0 && p.mouseX < p.width && p.mouseY > 0 && p.mouseY < p.height) {
      pulseRadius = 150;
    }
  };

  p.keyPressed = () => {
    if (p.key === 'r' || p.key === 'R') {
      bgColor = p.random(0, 50);
    }
  };

  p.windowResized = () => {
    p.resizeCanvas(p.windowWidth, p.windowHeight);
  };
};

new p5(pulseBomb);
```

### Reality Check

Vibes check failed if you skimmed that. Go back. Look at `p.map()`. That’s a needle mover. It takes a value (the current radius), understands its normal range (50 to 200), and translates it to a new range (0 to 255 for color). As the circle pulses outward, the color shifts from deep red to bright white. That’s not just drawing. That’s algorithmic thinking. That's mapping data to visuals.

You survived the first war zone. You know the difference between `setup()` and `draw()`. You know why Global Mode is a liability and why Instance Mode is your best friend. You know the origin is top-left, and you know how to tame the frame rate. You wired up inputs that actually do something.

But don't get cocky, slacker. This was just the canvas. You haven't drawn anything complex yet. You have a pulsing circle. It's cute. It's a start. But generative art is about geometry, chaos, and algorithms.

Next time, we load the **Geometric Ammo**. We're going to tear into primitives that actually bite. Triangles, quads, curves—weapons of mass creation. You bring the mindset, I'll bring the firepower. 

Your move, dreamer. See you in the trenches.

You think you're hot stuff because you spawned a canvas and slapped a rectangle on it? Cute. That's like a toddler finger-painting and calling themselves Basquiat. Your geometry game is weak, your shapes are soft, and your lines have less edge than a safety scissors. Time to fix that.

You survived the Canvas Bootcamp. You know your Global Mode from your Instance Mode. You dodged the Window Resize Trap. Good for you, chief. But knowing how to hold the weapon doesn't mean you know how to shoot. Right now, your canvas is an empty war zone, and you're standing there with a butter knife.

Let's load up the real geometric ammo. Points, lines, curves, custom vertices—the whole armory. By the time we're done, you won't just be drawing shapes. You'll be conducting spatial warfare.

## Core Carnage (Rip Apart the Essentials)

### The Stock Arsenal: Point, Line, Rect, Ellipse, Arc

You've seen these functions. You probably think you understand them. You don't. You've been using them like a caveman banging rocks together. Let's break down each one with surgical precision.

**Point.** The smallest unit of spatial existence. A single coordinate. A pixel-sized sniper shot on your canvas. You call `point(x, y)` and boom—existence. But here's where you're already messing up: you're not controlling the stroke weight. A point at `strokeWeight(1)` is a whisper. A point at `strokeWeight(8)` is a goddamn exclamation mark. Points aren't just positions—they're visual punctuation. Use them like you mean it.

**Line.** The connection between two realities. `line(x1, y1, x2, y2)`. Simple, right? Wrong. That line carries weight, attitude, and direction. A hairline stroke at `strokeWeight(0.5)` feels like a whisper across the canvas. A brutal `strokeWeight(12)` line feels like a crack in reality. And if you're not thinking about stroke caps—`ROUND`, `SQUARE`, `PROJECT`—you're leaving style on the table like a rookie leaving chips at a casino.

**Rect.** The rectangle. Four corners, four sides, zero excuses. `rect(x, y, w, h)`. But wait—there's a fifth parameter. `rect(x, y, w, h, r)` gives you rounded corners. Suddenly your rigid box has curves. And if you want different radii on each corner? `rect(x, y, w, h, tl, tr, br, bl)`. Eight parameters. Eight chances to make something interesting instead of another boring-ass box.

**Ellipse.** The circle's cooler older sibling. `ellipse(x, y, w, h)`. Set width and height equal, you get a circle. Set them different, you get an ellipse. But here's the thing that trips up half you slackers: the x and y refer to the CENTER of the ellipse, not the top-left corner like rect. Mix that up and your spatial calculations are toast. Your whole composition shifts by half the ellipse's dimensions and you're sitting there wondering why nothing lines up. Stay sharp.

**Arc.** The arc is where geometry starts getting dangerous. `arc(x, y, w, h, start, stop)`. You're not just drawing a shape—you're carving a slice out of existence. The start and stop parameters are in RADIANS, not degrees. You forgot that, didn't you? Yeah, you did. Use `PI`, `TWO_PI`, `HALF_PI` or the `radians()` function, or your arc is going to look like a drunken pie chart.

And the seventh parameter—the one that separates the pros from the posers: `arc(x, y, w, h, start, stop, mode)`. `OPEN` gives you just the arc curve. `CHORD` closes it with a straight line. `PIE` makes it a literal pie slice. Choose wrong and your visual vocabulary sounds like a toddler mumbling.

> ⚠️ **Common Mistake:** You're calling `ellipse()` with `ellipseMode(CORNER)` still set from three functions ago, then wondering why your circle is positioned in the wrong spot. Mode functions are sticky—they persist until you change them. Always set your mode explicitly before the shape that needs it. No assumptions. No hoping. Set it, draw it, move on.

### Stroke, Fill, and the Art of Not Making Mud

Here's where intermediate artists turn into mud-painters. You layer shape on top of shape, color on top of color, and suddenly your canvas looks like a brown soup of despair. What went wrong? You didn't respect the layering order. You didn't control your opacity. You didn't use blend modes with intention.

**Stroke and fill are not optional.** They're the skin and skeleton of every shape. `noStroke()` when you don't want an outline. `noFill()` when you want hollow forms. But set these BEFORE you draw the shape, not after. p5.js reads your instructions sequentially—like a recipe. You don't bake the cake and then add the flour.

**Opacity is your secret weapon.** `fill(255, 0, 0, 50)` gives you red at roughly 20% opacity. Layer that over blue and you get purple where they meet. But here's the thing—layer too many semi-transparent shapes and you get mud. The colors stack, mix, and cancel each other out. It's like a band where everyone's playing a different song. Noise.

**Blend modes change the game entirely.** `blendMode(ADD)` makes overlapping shapes brighten each other—perfect for light effects, glows, anything that should feel luminous. `blendMode(MULTIPLY)` darkens overlaps—great for shadows and depth. `blendMode(SCREEN)` is like ADD's softer cousin. But here's the critical part: **BLEND MODES ARE STICKY.** You set `blendMode(ADD)`, draw your glowing orb, and then forget to reset it. Now every shape after that orb is adding brightness to everything. Your canvas blows out to white. Game over.

> 💡 **Pro Tip:** Always reset to `blendMode(BLEND)` after using any alternative blend mode. Treat it like putting a gun back in its holster. You draw, you holster. Draw, holster. Every single time. No exceptions.

### Custom Shapes: beginShape, vertex, curveVertex

The stock primitives are your training wheels. Custom shapes are the motorcycle. Dangerous, fast, and way more fun.

`beginShape()` tells p5.js: "Listen up. I'm about to drop some vertices." Then you feed it points one by one with `vertex(x, y)`. Each vertex is a corner—a hard point where the shape changes direction. Close it with `endShape(CLOSE)` and you've got a polygon.

```javascript
beginShape();
vertex(100, 200);
vertex(300, 150);
vertex(350, 400);
vertex(80, 380);
endShape(CLOSE);
```

Boom. Custom quadrilateral. No stock primitive can touch this. You define every corner. You control every edge.

But hard corners aren't always what you want. Sometimes you need curves. That's where `curveVertex(x, y)` comes in. It creates smooth Catmull-Rom splines that pass through your points like silk. But here's the catch that trips up everyone: **curveVertex needs control points.** The first and last points in a curveVertex sequence aren't drawn—they're anchors that define the curve's direction at the start and end. Skip them and your curve gets chopped off.

```javascript
beginShape();
curveVertex(100, 200); // Control point—not drawn
curveVertex(100, 200); // First visible point
curveVertex(300, 150);
curveVertex(350, 400);
curveVertex(80, 380);
curveVertex(80, 380);  // Last visible point
curveVertex(80, 380);  // Control point—not drawn
endShape();
```

Yeah, you see that? You need to duplicate the first and last points. The outer duplicates are ghost points—control handles that shape the curve but don't appear on screen. Forget them and your curve looks like it got a bad haircut. Still with me, or you zoning out already?

And then there's `bezierVertex(cx1, cy1, cx2, cy2, x, y)`. Two control handles, one endpoint. This is the big leagues. Bezier curves give you ultimate control but demand respect. You start with a regular `vertex()` for the first point, then chain `bezierVertex()` calls. Each one pulls the curve toward its control points before landing on the endpoint. Master this and you can draw anything—typography, organic forms, flowing rivers of visual data.

### Bounding Boxes: The Invisible Cage

Every shape you draw exists within a bounding box—an invisible rectangle that defines its spatial footprint. For stock primitives, this is straightforward. A `rect(x, y, w, h)` IS its own bounding box. An `ellipse(x, y, w, h)` has a bounding box from `(x - w/2, y - h/2)` to `(x + w/2, y + h/2)`.

But custom shapes? That's on you, chief. You need to track the minimum and maximum x and y values across all your vertices. Why does this matter? Collision detection. Layout algorithms. Spatial partitioning. If you don't know where your shape's boundaries are, you can't control how it interacts with anything else on the canvas.

```javascript
let minX = Infinity, minY = Infinity;
let maxX = -Infinity, maxY = -Infinity;

// After defining all vertices...
let bbox = {
  x: minX,
  y: minY,
  w: maxX - minX,
  h: maxY - minY
};
```

> 🎯 **Key Insight:** A bounding box is your shape's ID card. It tells you the minimum spatial footprint of any form you've drawn. When you start building complex compositions—grids, tessellations, particle systems—bounding boxes are how you prevent chaos. You calculate them, you track them, you use them to make decisions. No bounding box, no control.

## Street Smarts (How to Wield This in the Wild)

Enough theory. Let's get tactical. Here's how this ammo performs when the rubber meets the road.

### Scenario 1: The Layered Composition That Doesn't Suck

You want to build a composition with depth—overlapping shapes, transparency, and visual hierarchy. Here's how you don't turn it into mud.

Start with your background layer. Full opacity. Solid color. This is your foundation. Then add your midground shapes at 60-80% opacity. These are your secondary forms—they exist but they don't scream. Finally, your foreground elements come in at full opacity with the boldest strokes. That's your visual hierarchy: background whispers, midground talks, foreground shouts.

```javascript
// Background—shut up and be solid
background(20, 25, 40);

// Midground—speak up but don't yell
noStroke();
fill(100, 150, 200, 80);
rect(100, 100, 300, 200);

fill(200, 100, 100, 80);
ellipse(350, 250, 250, 250);

// Foreground—SCREAM
fill(255, 220, 100);
stroke(255);
strokeWeight(3);
beginShape();
vertex(200, 150);
vertex(320, 180);
vertex(300, 320);
vertex(180, 290);
endShape(CLOSE);
```

See what happened there? The semi-transparent shapes create depth through color mixing. The opaque foreground shape pops forward because it's not competing with the layers behind it. That's spatial vocabulary, dreamer. That's geometry with intention.

### Scenario 2: The Custom Shape That Actually Means Something

Stop drawing random polygons. Every custom shape should have a purpose. Let's say you're building a generative crystal system. Each crystal is a custom shape with vertices determined by—you guessed it—math.

```javascript
function drawCrystal(x, y, size, points) {
  beginShape();
  for (let i = 0; i < points; i++) {
    let angle = (TWO_PI / points) * i;
    // Alternate between outer and inner radius
    let r = i % 2 === 0 ? size : size * 0.4;
    let px = x + cos(angle) * r;
    let py = y + sin(angle) * r;
    vertex(px, py);
  }
  endShape(CLOSE);
}

// Deploy it
push();
translate(width / 2, height / 2);
stroke(255, 100, 200);
strokeWeight(2);
noFill();
drawCrystal(0, 0, 150, 12);
pop();
```

That's a twelve-pointed star crystal. But the function is parameterized—change the `points` argument and you get a different form. Change the `size` ratio and you get sharper or flatter spikes. This isn't just drawing. This is building a system. You're not making one shape; you're making a shape GENERATOR.

Oh, sure, you could just hard-code every shape like a peasant. But why would you? Parameterized functions mean one change ripples through your entire composition. That's efficiency. That's power. That's not being a slacker.

### Scenario 3: Blend Modes as Spatial Strategy

Blend modes aren't just effects—they're spatial tools. When two shapes overlap, the blend mode determines what happens in that overlapping territory. It's like two gangs fighting over the same block—the blend mode is the rules of engagement.

```javascript
background(0);

// Additive blending for light-like behavior
blendMode(ADD);
fill(255, 0, 0, 150);
ellipse(width * 0.4, height * 0.5, 300, 300);

fill(0, 255, 0, 150);
ellipse(width * 0.5, height * 0.5, 300, 300);

fill(0, 0, 255, 150);
ellipse(width * 0.6, height * 0.5, 300, 300);

blendMode(BLEND); // Holster the weapon
```

Three overlapping circles with additive blending. Where red and green overlap, you get yellow. Where green and blue overlap, you get cyan. Where all three meet, you get white. That's not just pretty—that's color theory made spatial. The overlap regions BECOME new colors. You're generating visual information from negative space.

But forget that `blendMode(BLEND)` reset at the end and your next `background()` call will behave strangely. On some setups, additive blend mode persists into the background fill, turning your dark canvas into a bright mess. The gun is still firing. Holster it.

### Scenario 4: Bounding Box Driven Layout

You've got a custom shape and you need to make sure it doesn't overlap with another custom shape. Bounding box collision. Simple, fast, essential.

```javascript
function getBoundingBox(vertices) {
  let minX = Infinity, minY = Infinity;
  let maxX = -Infinity, maxY = -Infinity;

  for (let v of vertices) {
    minX = min(minX, v.x);
    minY = min(minY, v.y);
    maxX = max(maxX, v.x);
    maxY = max(maxY, v.y);
  }

  return { x: minX, y: minY, w: maxX - minX, h: maxY - minY };
}

function boxesOverlap(a, b) {
  return !(a.x + a.w < b.x || 
           b.x + b.w < a.x || 
           a.y + a.h < b.y || 
           b.y + b.h < a.y);
}
```

That's it. That's collision detection in its simplest form. Two bounding boxes. Check if they overlap. If they do, your shapes might be colliding. If they don't, they definitely aren't. It's not pixel-perfect, but it's fast, and fast matters when you're running hundreds of shapes at sixty frames per second.

> ☕ **Real Talk:** You don't need pixel-perfect collision for generative art. You need "close enough" collision that runs fast and looks right. Bounding boxes are the 80/20 solution—80% of the accuracy for 20% of the computation. Use them. Love them. Stop over-engineering your spatial checks.

### Scenario 5: The Curve That Doesn't Suck

Curves are where intermediate artists hit a wall. They try `curveVertex` once, get a weird truncated spline, and run back to straight lines. Not you. Not anymore.

```javascript
// A flowing organic curve
noFill();
stroke(255);
strokeWeight(2);

beginShape();
// First control point—duplicated first visible point
curveVertex(50, 300);
// Visible curve points
curveVertex(50, 300);
curveVertex(150, 100);
curveVertex(300, 400);
curveVertex(450, 150);
curveVertex(550, 350);
// Last visible point duplicated
curveVertex(550, 350);
// Final control point
curveVertex(550, 350);
endShape();
```

That curve flows through six points like a river through a canyon. Smooth. Organic. No hard corners. But remove those duplicated control points and watch the curve get clipped at both ends. It'll look like someone took scissors to it. The control points define the tangent direction at the start and end of the curve—they tell the spline "head this way when you leave this point." Without them, the curve doesn't know where to go, so it just... stops early.

