# Module 1: Canvas Bootcamp: Your First War Zone

You picked up a pencil once in third grade, drew a lopsided house, and thought, "Yeah, I'm an artist." Cute story, bro. But you're not in art class anymore. You're stepping into the algorithmic trenches, where the canvas isn't paper—it's a coordinate grid that will skull-drag you if you don't learn its rules. You want to make generative art that makes jaws drop? You gotta survive bootcamp first.

Still with me, or you zoning out already? Good. Let's strip this down to the brass tacks.

## Core Carnage (Rip Apart the Essentials)

You think you can just open a text editor and start splashing pixels around? Oh, sure, skip the basics—because mediocrity's a great look on you. You need to know the battlefield before you pull the trigger. p5.js is your weapon. It’s a JavaScript library built to make coding visual for artists and designers, but don't let the friendly intro fool you. Under the hood, it’s a ruthless rendering engine. If you feed it garbage logic, it will spit out a blank screen and laugh at you.

### The Two Modes: Global vs. Instance

Listen up, chief. p5.js gives you two ways to enter the ring. 

**Global Mode** is the default. It’s the bare-knuckle street fight. You just drop your functions right into the global scope.

```javascript
function setup() {
  createCanvas(800, 600);
}

function draw() {
  background(0);
  circle(mouseX, mouseY, 50);
}
```

Simple, right? Maybe too simple. Global mode pollutes the namespace. Every variable you declare globally is a loaded gun pointed at your own foot. You write `var speed` up top, and boom—some other library or script just hijacked it. 

Enter **Instance Mode**. This is the tactical, silenced-assassin approach. You wrap your entire sketch in a function, locking your variables in a tight little cage where nobody else can touch them. 

```javascript
const sketch = (p) => {
  let speed = 2;

  p.setup = () => {
    p.createCanvas(800, 600);
  };

  p.draw = () => {
    p.background(0);
    p.circle(p.mouseX, p.mouseY, 50);
  };
};

new p5(sketch);
```

> ⚠️ **Common Mistake:** Copy-pasting Global Mode sketches into a modern React or Vue app and watching the whole DOM burn to the ground. If you're embedding p5.js anywhere near other code, Instance Mode isn't an option. It's a survival requirement.

You see the difference? Instance mode makes you prefix everything with `p.`. It looks tedious, but it’s your armor. If you’re just prototyping in the p5 Web Editor, go global. But the second you ship this to a real webpage, suit up with Instance Mode.

### The Grid: Owning the Coordinate Origin

Let me guess—you think (0,0) is the center of the screen? Highkey delusional. This isn't high school geometry. In p5.js, (0,0) is the top-left corner. Always has been. Always will be.

X moves right. Y moves down. Wrap your head around that right now, because the moment you try to plot a shape and it flies off the screen, it's because you assumed Y goes up. It doesn't. Y goes down like your motivation on a Monday morning.

You want to move the origin? You want (0,0) in the center where it belongs? You manipulate the canvas. 

```javascript
function setup() {
  createCanvas(800, 600);
  // Move the origin to the center of the canvas
  translate(width / 2, height / 2);
}
```

Wait, no! Stop! If you put `translate()` in `setup()`, it only happens once. The canvas resets its matrix every time `draw()` runs. We'll get to that in a second, but understand this: `width` and `height` are built-in variables. They tell you the size of your war zone. Use them. Never hardcode `400` when you mean `width / 2`. You change the canvas size later, and your whole sketch breaks. Be smarter than the code.

### Canvas Size and Pixel Density

You think an 800x600 canvas is just 800 by 600 pixels? Oh, you sweet summer child. Welcome to the era of high-DPI displays. Your fancy MacBook Retina screen doesn't render one pixel per pixel—it renders two. Or three! If you don't control your pixel density, your crisp generative lines will look like blurry garbage.

By default, p5.js calls `pixelDensity(displayDensity())`. It tries to match your monitor. Sometimes that’s fine. But when you start doing heavy pixel manipulation later in this journey, that 2x density will melt your frame rate into slag.

> 💡 **Pro Tip:** Force `pixelDensity(1)` in your `setup()` if you care about raw performance over hyper-crisp edges. It halves the pixel workload. Your GPU will thank you.

### The Lifecycle: setup() vs draw()

This is the heart of the beast. The engine. The lifecycle. If you don't get this, you're just a tourist taking screenshots.

`setup()` runs exactly once. One time. One trigger pull. You set up your environment here. Canvas size, frame rate, loading fonts, initializing arrays. You do NOT draw shapes in `setup()`. You don't animate in `setup()`. It’s the prep work before the brawl.

`draw()` runs on a loop. Over. And over. And over. By default, it tries to run 60 times a second. 60 frames per second. Every time `draw()` fires, it draws a new frame. If you don't clear the screen, it just draws over the last frame. 

```javascript
function setup() {
  createCanvas(800, 600);
  background(25); // Dark grey background, runs ONCE
}

function draw() {
  // No background() here!
  circle(mouseX, mouseY, 20);
}
```

What happens here? You get a trailing trail of circles following your mouse. Why? Because the canvas isn't being wiped. The previous frame bleeds into the next one. It's a slick trick for motion blur, but if you actually want a static shape moving across a clean background, you better put `background()` inside `draw()`.

> 🎯 **Key Insight:** The `draw()` loop is an illusion. It's not a continuous flow of ink. It's a flipbook. Every frame, p5.js renders the entire state of your canvas. If your code is slow, the flipbook stutters. That stutter is called "dropping frames."

### Frame Rate: Your Leash

You think you're the boss of the canvas? You're not. The frame rate is your leash. `frameRate(60)` sets the target. But if your `draw()` function has to calculate 10,000 particle collisions, it’s going to take longer than 16.67 milliseconds. And when it takes longer, the frame rate drops. 

You can check your real-time FPS with `frameRate()`. Print it to the console. Watch it. If it dips below 60, your code is bloated. You're asking the browser to do too much heavy lifting. 

Excuses? Cute. But winners bleed sweat, not stories. If your sketch lags, you optimize. You don't blame the browser. 

### Input: Proving It Ain't a Static Screenshot

A painting is dead. A generative sketch breathes. It reacts. It bites back. If your art doesn't respond to the user, it’s just a screenshot with extra steps.

p5.js hands you `mouseX` and `mouseY` on a silver platter. Two built-in variables that constantly update with the cursor's position. Use them. 

But what about clicks? What about the keyboard?

```javascript
function mousePressed() {
  // This fires ONCE per click. Not every frame.
  console.log("BANG!");
}

function keyPressed() {
  // Fires once when a key goes down.
  if (key === ' ') {
    console.log("Spacebar hit.");
  }
}
```

> ⚠️ **Common Mistake:** Putting input logic directly inside `draw()` without state tracking. If you check `if (mouseIsPressed)` inside `draw()`, it will fire 60 times a second while the button is held down. If you want a single action per click, use the `mousePressed()` event function. Period.

You want to map the spacebar to reset the canvas? Put it in `keyPressed()`. You want a particle to spawn continuously while the mouse is down? Use `mouseIsPressed` inside `draw()`. Know the difference. Own the input.

## Street Smarts (How to Wield This in the Wild)

Alright, dreamer. You got the theory. You know the lifecycle. You know the grid. Now let's get our hands dirty. I'm not letting you copy-paste a tutorial. We're going to build a reactive, frame-rate-aware sketch from scratch, and I'm going to explain every single scalpel cut.

### The Scenario: The Pulse Bomb

We’re going to build a pulse bomb. A circle that sits in the dead center of the canvas, pulsing based on a sine wave. When you click the mouse, it explodes outward, resetting the pulse. When you hit 'R', the background flips. And we’re going to do it in Instance Mode, because we aren't amateurs.

**Step 1: The Setup and the Armor**

Open a blank file. We define the sketch closure.

```javascript
const pulseBomb = (p) => {
  let pulseRadius = 50;
  let bgColor = 10;

  p.setup = () => {
    p.createCanvas(p.windowWidth, p.windowHeight);
    p.frameRate(60);
    p.noStroke();
  };
```

Look at that. `p.windowWidth` and `p.windowHeight`. We aren't hardcoding 800x600. We're taking up the whole damn browser window. We set the frame rate to 60 to establish the leash. `p.noStroke()` because outlines are for coloring books, and we want clean, filled shapes.

**Step 2: The Draw Loop and the Math**

Now we need the pulse. How do you make a circle breathe? You use `p.sin()`. Sine waves oscillate between -1 and 1. We map that to a radius.

```javascript
  p.draw = () => {
    p.background(bgColor);

    // Move origin to center
    p.translate(p.width / 2, p.height / 2);

    // Calculate the pulse
    // p.frameCount is a built-in variable that counts frames.
    let pulse = p.sin(p.frameCount * 0.05) * 50;
    let currentRadius = pulseRadius + pulse;

    p.fill(255, 0, 0); // Red like blood
    p.circle(0, 0, currentRadius * 2); // circle takes diameter, not radius!
  };
```

Did you catch that? `p.circle()` takes the diameter, not the radius. How many rookies have screwed that up? Millions. You multiply by 2, or you look like a fool with a tiny dot on the screen.

Also, notice `p.background(bgColor)` is inside `draw()`. This wipes the slate clean every single frame. Without it, the red circle would smear across the screen as it pulses. We want a clean pulse, so we wipe it.

**Step 3: The Interaction**

A pulsing circle is nice. But it's still just a screensaver. Let's make it violent. When the user clicks, we want the radius to spike.

```javascript
  p.mousePressed = () => {
    // Only trigger if the click is inside the canvas
    if (p.mouseX > 0 && p.mouseX < p.width && p.mouseY > 0 && p.mouseY < p.height) {
      pulseRadius = 150; // Spike the radius
    }
  };
```

Wait, if we just set `pulseRadius = 150`, it will stay at 150 forever. The pulse will just be bigger. We need it to decay back to normal. We add a decay mechanic inside `draw()`.

Update the `draw()` loop:

```javascript
  p.draw = () => {
    p.background(bgColor);
    p.translate(p.width / 2, p.height / 2);

    let pulse = p.sin(p.frameCount * 0.05) * 50;
    let currentRadius = pulseRadius + pulse;

    p.fill(255, 0, 0);
    p.circle(0, 0, currentRadius * 2);

    // Decay the radius back to 50
    if (pulseRadius > 50) {
      pulseRadius -= 2; // Shrink by 2 pixels every frame
    }
  };
```

Now we're talking. You click, the circle balloons to 150, and then it shrinks by 2 pixels every frame until it settles back at 50. It's alive. It reacts.

**Step 4: The Keyboard Flank**

Let's wire up the 'R' key to reset the background. 

```javascript
  p.keyPressed = () => {
    if (p.key === 'r' || p.key === 'R') {
      bgColor = p.random(0, 50); // Random dark background
    }
  };
```

> ☕ **Real Talk:** Notice I didn't just say `if (key == 'r')`. Users hit Caps Lock. Users hold Shift. You check for both, or your app feels broken. Details matter, chief. The streets are unforgiving.

**Step 5: The Window Resize Trap**

You think you're done? You refresh the page, it looks beautiful. Then you resize your browser window. What happens? The canvas stays the same size, or it distorts. You forgot the resize handler.

```javascript
  p.windowResized = () => {
    p.resizeCanvas(p.windowWidth, p.windowHeight);
  };
```

Boom. Now when the user stretches the browser, the canvas stretches with it. The origin recalculates to the new center every frame because we used `p.width / 2` in `draw()`. Flexible. Lethal. Unbreakable.

### The Full Arsenal

Here is the complete, unadulterated code. Read it. Understand it. Do not copy it without tracing every single line with your own eyes.

```javascript
const pulseBomb = (p) => {
  let pulseRadius = 50;
  let bgColor = 10;

  p.setup = () => {
    p.createCanvas(p.windowWidth, p.windowHeight);
    p.frameRate(60);
    p.noStroke();
  };

  p.draw = () => {
    p.background(bgColor);
    p.translate(p.width / 2, p.height / 2);

    let pulse = p.sin(p.frameCount * 0.05) * 50;
    let currentRadius = pulseRadius + pulse;

    // Color shifts from red to white as it expands
    let colorShift = p.map(currentRadius, 50, 200, 0, 255);
    p.fill(255, colorShift, colorShift);

    p.circle(0, 0, currentRadius * 2);

    if (pulseRadius > 50) {
      pulseRadius -= 2;
    }
  };

  p.mousePressed = () => {
    if (p.mouseX > 0 && p.mouseX < p.width && p.mouseY > 0 && p.mouseY < p.height) {
      pulseRadius = 150;
    }
  };

  p.keyPressed = () => {
    if (p.key === 'r' || p.key === 'R') {
      bgColor = p.random(0, 50);
    }
  };

  p.windowResized = () => {
    p.resizeCanvas(p.windowWidth, p.windowHeight);
  };
};

new p5(pulseBomb);
```

### Reality Check

Vibes check failed if you skimmed that. Go back. Look at `p.map()`. That’s a needle mover. It takes a value (the current radius), understands its normal range (50 to 200), and translates it to a new range (0 to 255 for color). As the circle pulses outward, the color shifts from deep red to bright white. That’s not just drawing. That’s algorithmic thinking. That's mapping data to visuals.

You survived the first war zone. You know the difference between `setup()` and `draw()`. You know why Global Mode is a liability and why Instance Mode is your best friend. You know the origin is top-left, and you know how to tame the frame rate. You wired up inputs that actually do something.

But don't get cocky, slacker. This was just the canvas. You haven't drawn anything complex yet. You have a pulsing circle. It's cute. It's a start. But generative art is about geometry, chaos, and algorithms.

Next time, we load the **Geometric Ammo**. We're going to tear into primitives that actually bite. Triangles, quads, curves—weapons of mass creation. You bring the mindset, I'll bring the firepower. 

